{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"205"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/205"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.05,0.09,0.06,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"205"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/205"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"205"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62727"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of sudden onset low back pain that occurred while bending to pick up a newspaper. The pain is continuous and worsens with movement. He has a medical history of prostate cancer treated with prostatectomy four years ago and goserelin for the past year. He takes no other regular medications. He lives independently and is usually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness on palpation of the L3-L4 spinous processes but no paraspinal muscle tenderness. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is normal. Investigations from three weeks ago show prostate specific antigen (PSA) 0.8 ng/mL (0-4.0) and a nuclear medicine bone scan negative for metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar disc herniation","Osteoarthritis","Metastatic vertebral deposit","Muscle spasm","Osteoporotic vertebral fracture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute back pain and risk factors for osteoporosis, most notably androgen deprivation therapy with goserelin. The mechanism of injury, examination findings, and recent normal cancer surveillance are most consistent with an osteoporotic vertebral fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoporotic vertebral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s age, sudden onset with minimal trauma, and use of goserelin. Androgen deprivation therapy can cause significant bone loss within six months of initiation, greatly increasing fracture risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar disc herniation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with radicular symptoms and neurological findings, which are absent in this case. The mechanism of injury and examination findings are more consistent with a bony rather than disc pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes chronic, gradually progressive pain rather than acute onset. While this patient may have underlying spinal osteoarthritis given his age, it would not explain the sudden onset of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic vertebral deposit\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the recent normal bone scan and PSA. Metastatic disease typically causes gradual onset pain rather than acute symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle spasm\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes diffuse paraspinal tenderness rather than focal spinous process tenderness. The persistence of pain and mechanism of injury are more suggestive of bony pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising the significance of androgen deprivation therapy as a risk factor for osteoporosis, and that minimal trauma can cause vertebral fractures in at-risk patients. Further imaging (typically X-ray or CT) would be needed to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-androgen therapy significantly increases osteoporosis risk within six months of treatment initiation","Sudden onset back pain in elderly patients on androgen deprivation therapy should raise suspicion for osteoporotic vertebral fracture","Recent normal bone scan and PSA help exclude metastatic disease as a cause of new back pain"],"references":["Will JS, Bury DC, Miller JA. Mechanical low back pain. American family physician. 2018 Oct 1;98(7):421-8.","van Oostwaard MM, van den Bergh JP, van de Wouw Y, Janssen-Heijnen M, de Jong M, Wyers CE. High prevalence of vertebral fractures at initiation of androgen deprivation therapy for prostate cancer. J Bone Oncol. 2022 Dec 7;38:100465. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9798166/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"205"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T12:50:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T09:20:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"205"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/